ricing Data](https://deepwiki.com/gridstatus/gridstatusio/4.4-ercot-pricing-data)\n* [Development Guide](https://deepwiki.com/gridstatus/gridstatusio/5-development-guide)\n* [Development Setup](https://deepwiki.com/gridstatus/gridstatusio/5.1-development-setup)\n* [Testing](https://deepwiki.com/gridstatus/gridstatusio/5.2-testing)\n* [Code Quality Tools](https://deepwiki.com/gridstatus/gridstatusio/5.3-code-quality-tools)\n* [Release Process](https://deepwiki.com/gridstatus/gridstatusio/5.4-release-process)\nMenu\n# ISO Hubs and Zones\nRelevant source files\n* [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb]()\n* [gridstatusio/tests/test\\_timezone\\_behavior.py](https://github.com/gridstatus/gridstatusio/blob/7990f3d3/gridstatusio/tests/test_timezone_behavior.py)\n## Purpose and Scope\nThis document explains how to work with ISO hubs and pricing zones data using the GridStatus.io API. It covers how to identify, filter, and retrieve hub and zone price data across different Independent System Operators (ISOs) and Regional Transmission Organizations (RTOs) in North America. This information is essential for electricity market analysis, trading strategies, and understanding regional price differentials.\n## Introduction to ISO Hubs and Zones\nIn electricity markets, hubs and zones are aggregation points or regions where prices are calculated and published. These locations serve as important reference points for electricity trading, financial settlement, and market analysis:\n* **Hubs**: Trading points that typically represent an average of multiple pricing nodes, designed to provide a representative price for a region\n* **Zones**: Geographical areas within an ISO/RTO territory, often corresponding to utility service territories or transmission constraints\nDifferent ISOs organize and name their hubs and zones in distinct ways, making it important to understand the specific terminology and filtering approaches for each market.\n```\n<!--$!--><template data-dgst=\"BAILOUT_TO_CLIENT_SIDE_RENDERING\"></template><!--/$-->\n```\nSources: [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb7-11]()\n## Accessing Hub and Zone Data\nThe GridStatusClient provides a consistent interface for accessing hub and zone data across all markets through the `get\\_dataset` method. To retrieve hub or zone data, you need to:\n1. Identify the correct dataset (e.g., `ercot\\_spp\\_real\\_time\\_15\\_min`, `pjm\\_lmp\\_real\\_time\\_5\\_min`)\n2. Filter by the appropriate `location\\_type` value\n3. Optionally further filter by location name patterns\n```\n<!--$!--><template data-dgst=\"BAILOUT_TO_CLIENT_SIDE_RENDERING\"></template><!--/$-->\n```\nSources: [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb30-34]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb141-148]()\n## ISO-Specific Hub and Zone Implementations\nEach ISO/RTO implements hubs and zones differently. Here's a detailed breakdown by market:\n### SPP\nThe Southwest Power Pool has two primary hubs in their LMP data:\n* SPPNORTH\\_HUB\n* SPPSOUTH\\_HUB\nTo retrieve SPP hub data:\n```\n<div class=\"rounded-sm border border-[#8F8F8F]/30 p-2 text-xs font-normal leading-[15px]\" style=\"background-color:transparent;min-height:2em\"></div>\n```\nSources: [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb41-44]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb141-148]()\n### MISO\nMISO labels many nodes as \"Hub\" in their data, but there are a specific subset that represent state-level hubs that analysts typically focus on. You can filter first by `location\\_type` of \"Hub\" and then further filter the results based on location names:\n```\n<div class=\"rounded-sm border border-[#8F8F8F]/30 p-2 text-xs font-normal leading-[15px]\" style=\"background-color:transparent;min-height:2em\"></div>\n```\nThe state-level hubs in MISO include:\n* ARKANSAS.HUB\n* ILLINOIS.HUB\n* INDIANA.HUB\n* LOUISIANA.HUB\n* MICHIGAN.HUB\n* MINN.HUB\n* MS.HUB\n* TEXAS.HUB\nSources: [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb156-158]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb336-345]()\n### ERCOT\nERCOT publishes data for 5 trading hubs plus two averages (one for buses and one for hubs):\nTrading Hubs:\n* HB\\_HOUSTON\n* HB\\_NORTH\n* HB\\_PAN\n* HB\\_SOUTH\n* HB\\_WEST\nAverages:\n* HB\\_BUSAVG\n* HB\\_HUBAVG\n```\n<div class=\"rounded-sm border border-[#8F8F8F]/30 p-2 text-xs font-normal leading-[15px]\" style=\"background-color:transparent;min-height:2em\"></div>\n```\nERCOT also publishes data for 8 load zones:\n* LZ\\_AEN\n* LZ\\_CPS\n* LZ\\_HOUSTON\n* LZ\\_LCRA\n* LZ\\_NORTH\n* LZ\\_RAYBN\n* LZ\\_SOUTH\n* LZ\\_WEST\n```\n<div class=\"rounded-sm border border-[#8F8F8F]/30 p-2 text-xs font-normal leading-[15px]\" style=\"background-color:transparent;min-height:2em\"></div>\n```\nSources: [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb353-355]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb495-502]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb510-511]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb662-669]()\n### CAISO\nThe California ISO has 3 trading hubs:\n* TH\\_NP15\\_GEN-APND (Northern California)\n* TH\\_SP15\\_GEN-APND (Southern California)\n* TH\\_ZP26\\_GEN-APND (Central California)\n```\n<div class=\"rounded-sm border border-[#8F8F8F]/30 p-2 text-xs font-normal leading-[15px]\" style=\"background-color:transparent;min-height:2em\"></div>\n```\nCAISO also publishes data for Default Load Aggregation Points (DLAPs), which are the points at which all bids for demand are submitted and settled:\n* DLAP\\_PACE\\_NPM-APND\n* DLAP\\_PACW\\_NPM-APND\n* DLAP\\_PGAE-APND (PG&E)\n* DLAP\\_SCE-APND (Southern California Edison)\n* DLAP\\_SDGE-APND (San Diego Gas & Electric)\n* DLAP\\_VEA-APND (Valley Electric Association)\n```\n<div class=\"rounded-sm border border-[#8F8F8F]/30 p-2 text-xs font-normal leading-[15px]\" style=\"background-color:transparent;min-height:2em\"></div>\n```\nSources: [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb677-679]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb787-794]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb801-803]() [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipynb953-959]()\n### PJM\nPJM, as the largest electricity market in the US, has the most hubs:\n* AEP-DAYTON HUB\n* AEP GEN HUB\n* ATSI GEN HUB\n* CHICAGO GEN HUB\n* CHICAGO HUB\n* DOMINION HUB\n* EASTERN HUB\n* NEW JERSEY HUB\n* N ILLINOIS HUB\n* OHIO HUB\n* WESTERN HUB\n* WEST INT HUB\n```\n<div class=\"rounded-sm border border-[#8F8F8F]/30 p-2 text-xs font-normal leading-[15px]\" style=\"background-color:transparent;min-height:2em\"></div>\n```\nSources: [Examples/ISO Hubs.ipy",
